	<Title>
		Recipe: Dilled shrimp salad on lettuce leaves
	</Title>
	<Abstract>
		Dilled shrimp salad on lettuce leaves &amp;mdash; one of many healthy recipes from Mayo Clinic.
	</Abstract>
	<ServingInfo Label="Serves">
		2
	</ServingInfo>
	<DietitianTip Label="Dietitian&apos;s tip">
		&lt;p&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Dietitian&apos;s tip:&lt;/strong&gt; This salad is best if it&apos;s made ahead of time and can chill well. If you aren&apos;t able to make it early, place the salad in the freezer and stir every 10 minutes.
&lt;/p&gt;
	</DietitianTip>
	<Directions Label="Directions">
		&lt;p&gt;
Fill a large pot 3/4 full with water and bring to a boil. Add the pasta and cook until al dente (tender), 10 to 12 minutes, or according to the package directions. Drain the pasta thoroughly and rinse under cold water.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
In a small saucepan, cover the asparagus with water. Bring to a boil and cook only until tender-crisp, about 3 to 5 minutes. Drain and rinse under cold water.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
In a small bowl, add the salad dressing and dill. Whisk to mix evenly.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
In a large bowl, add the pasta, asparagus, shrimp, tomatoes and scallions. Add the salad dressing mixture and toss to coat evenly. Cover and refrigerate until thoroughly chilled, about 1 hour.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
To serve, divide the watercress among the plates. Top with dilled salad and serve.
&lt;/p&gt;
	</Directions>
	<Ingredients Label="Ingredients">
		&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;2 cups uncooked farfalle (bow tie) pasta&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;4 fresh asparagus stalks, cut into 1/2-inch pieces&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1/4 cup reduced-fat salad dressing&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1 1/2 teaspoons fresh dill&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;1/2 pound cooked shrimp&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;5 to 8 cherry tomatoes, halved&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;4 scallions or green onions, diced&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;4 cups watercress or another type of salad greens&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
	</Ingredients>
